Subject:    Domain resolvers &amp; rfc953 "hostname" servers
From:       <a href="?a=95837785000003&r=1&w=2">skat.usc.edu!blarson () oberon ! usc ! edu  (Bob Larson)</a>
Date:       <a href="?l=namedroppers&r=1&w=2&b=198901">1989-01-04 9:49:47</a></font>
[Download RAW <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837784626771&q=mbox">message</a> or <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837784626771&q=raw">body</a>]</b>

We finally have tcp/ip (mostly) working on one of the primes on
campus.  (It can't handle the sri-nic host table.) Unfortunatly,
prime's tcp/ip dosn't support the domain name system yet, but it does
have the ability to query an rfc953 "hostname" server for additional
hostname to address translations.

Is there any software available to translate hostname queries to
normal domain queries?

Is there any software available to handle hostname queries at all?

Are any hosts besides sri-nic.arpa running such software?

I would like to also get reasonable mail running on this system.  What
MX resolution software is available?  (I've heard the name bind, but is
that a server or a resolver or both?)  Primos TCP/IP is loosly based on
4.3bsd, so a unix version would probably be the easiest to start from.
-- 
